    "abstractNote": "John of Ephesus did not merely catalog events but employed stylistic and organizational techniques to contextualize and direct his narrative. This is made apparent by the presentation of a series of clerical trials in the first book of his <i>Ecclesiastical History</i>. The <i>Ecclesiastical History</i> should be understood as playing a complementary role to his <i>Lives of the Eastern Saints</i>. Where the latter work presented the charismatic credentials of miracle-working saint-ascetics, the former showed the institutional soundness of the miaphysite hierarchy. He demonstrated this negatively through a chaotic account of the legal practices of the Chalcedonians.",
